Elena said she had no choice but to give into her husband’s violence. “It was one choice, to return down the road and remain with my parents and with my husband there as well,” she said. “Life in the naros’ is [miserable], I couldn’t maybe live there. “[The second choice] was that I return and beg [my husband] and kneel to him, then keep my honor, keep my children within my lap and provide food for them.” A woman returning from denouncing her husband’s attacks does not put receive the respect a self-respecting woman should get, said Dudnik. “She doesn’t get any support or any help,” Dudnik said. This post consist of a pile of “clippings” that I have accumulated over the past few years. A few of these I found, most I got from fellow travelers on the struggle for human rights. I hope there are more types of human rights than “traditional” human rights; that rights such as eating when members of your family are starving; freedom FROM fear to plane crashes, or terrorist attacks; freedom FROM respiratory illness caused by your factory bosses dumping toxic sludge on your back yard; even education, will be considered as basic parts of human existence.
